In July 2021, Paris 2024 president Tony Estanguet stated that the [[Paris_Organising_Committee_for_the_2024_Olympic_and_Paralympic_Games|organising committee]] was conducting a feasibility study on hosting the opening and closing ceremonies outside of a traditional stadium setting, so that they could "marry the best of Paris–the iconic sites–to the possibility of engaging with hundreds of thousands of people, maybe more."<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|date=2021-07-21|title=Paris 2024 to reveal city-centre Opening Ceremony locations by "end of the year"|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1110522/paris-2024-city-centre-opening-ceremony|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-14|website=www.insidethegames.biz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721153011/https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1110522/paris-2024-city-centre-opening-ceremony|archive-date=21 July 2021 }}</ref> This concept of an "open Games" was exemplified in the Paris 2024 handover presentation during the [[2020_Summer_Olympics_closing_ceremony|2020 closing ceremony]],<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|date=2021-07-21|title=Paris 2024 to reveal city-centre Opening Ceremony locations by "end of the year"|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1110522/paris-2024-city-centre-opening-ceremony|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-14|website=www.insidethegames.biz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721153011/https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1110522/paris-2024-city-centre-opening-ceremony|archive-date=21 July 2021 }}</ref> which featured a live segment from a viewing party at [[Trocadéro|Place du Trocadéro]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-08-08|title=The Tokyo Olympics end with Closing Ceremony|url=https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/tokyo-2020-olympics-08-08-21-spt/h_ace2957c9e578a1d0d2a927a1fd5c263|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-14|website=CNN|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810081821/https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/tokyo-2020-olympics-08-08-21-spt/h_ace2957c9e578a1d0d2a927a1fd5c263|archive-date=10 August 2021 }}</ref> Estanguet expected the sites for the ceremonies to be announced by the end of the year.<ref name=":1" />

On 13 December 2021, it was announced that the opening ceremony will feature athletes parade being [[Boat_parade|transported by boat]] from [[Pont_d'Austerlitz|Pont d'Austerlitz]] to [[Pont_d'Iéna|Pont d'Iéna]] along the [[Seine|Seine]] river. The {{Convert|6|km|miles|abbr=in}} route will pass landmarks such as the [[Louvre|Louvre]], [[Notre-Dame_de_Paris|Notre-Dame de Paris]], and [[Place_de_la_Concorde|Place de la Concorde]], and feature cultural presentations. The official protocol will take place at a 30.000 seat "mini-stadium" at the Trocadéro. Organisers stated that the ceremony would be the most "spectacular and accessible opening ceremony in Olympic history", with Estanguet stating that it would be free to attend, and estimating that it could attract as many as 600,000 spectators. The Trocadéro will also host the closing ceremonies as well.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-12-13|title=Paris 2024 confirms Seine will serve as venue for city centre Opening Ceremony|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1116787/paris-2024-opening-ceremony-plans|url-status=live|access-date=2021-12-14|website=www.insidethegames.biz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211213173023/https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1116787/paris-2024-opening-ceremony-plans|archive-date=13 December 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-12-13|title=Paris 2024 Olympic organisers reveal audacious plans for opening ceremony|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2021/dec/13/paris-2024-olympic-organisers-reveal-audacious-plans-for-opening-ceremony|access-date=2021-12-14|website=the Guardian|language=en|archive-date=2022-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220318121115/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2021/dec/13/paris-2024-olympic-organisers-reveal-audacious-plans-for-opening-ceremony}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-12-13|title=Paris to hold 'most accessible' opening ceremony of 2024 Olympics on River Seine|url=https://www.france24.com/en/sport/20211213-paris-to-hold-most-accessible-opening-ceremony-of-2024-olympics-on-river-seine|access-date=2021-12-14|website=France 24|language=en|archive-date=2022-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220417155143/https://www.france24.com/en/sport/20211213-paris-to-hold-most-accessible-opening-ceremony-of-2024-olympics-on-river-seine}}</ref>
